Plots and graphics that visualize data is one of the areas where R is strong. Actually, there are two major ways to produce graphics in R and we will demonstrate both ways using an example data set.

To demonstrate R’s plotting capabilities we will use a dataset on diamonds that ships with the ggplot2-package. Because the data set is so comprehensive we first randomly sub-sample 20 diamonds from each group defined by colour and cut quality and store the result under a new name diam. For this task, we use the dplyr-package. To have reproducible results from the sub-sampling we set the seed of the pseudo random-generator via set.seed. The resulting dataframe diam should contain 700 rows as we have 35 groups of diamonds in terms of colour and cut quality.

set.seed(1289)   # for reproducible results

# load diamonds data set from package "ggplot2"
# if not installed yet on your computer install once via:
# install.packages("ggplot2")
data(diamonds, package = "ggplot2")

diam <- diamonds |> 
  # randomly sample 20 observations per group defined by color & cut
  dplyr::slice_sample(n = 20, by = c(color, cut)) # sub-sampling with dplyr

1 Base graphics

From its early days on, R has provided quite impressive plotting capabilities built-in. These plot-routines are known as base-graphics. Most of these graphic functions reside in its internal graphics-package that is loaded automatically in every R session. Examples are the functions

  • barplot for a barplot
  • boxplot for a boxplot
  • plot for scatter plots

We show two base graphics examples that relate price to certain properties of the diamonds.

# left: scatter plot price (y-axis) versus carat (x-axis)
plot(price ~ carat, data = diam)
# right: boxplot price (y-axis) versus cut (x-axis)
boxplot(price ~ cut, data = diam)

There are a lot of common features shared by (most of) these base graphic functions.

  • Most notably, there is the formula-interface (like y ~ x, data = <dataframe>) with which one specifies the variables of a dataframe to plot on the y- and the x-axis. When a dataframe is provided via the data= parameter then you can directly use the column names unquoted (as if they were known variables in the R-session). The R interpreter will first look inside the given dataframe to find matching columns.
  • Furthermore, many base plot functions share common argument names like pch= (for plot character) or lty= (for line type).

Still, the base graphics system has grown slowly over time and can be quite confusing and diverse, lacking an overarching design. You have to explicitly request (i.e. to program) each feature (like a legend or which line type) you want to see on the plot.

2 ggplot2 graphics

In contrast, the add-on R-package ggplot2 was created by Hadley Wickham more than ten years after the inception of R to facilitate a coherent system to more declaratively create graphics. ggplot2 builds on the idea that a statistical graphic in essence maps the data to the aesthetic attributes (like colour, shape or size) of geometric objects (like points, lines or bars).

You provide the data, tell ggplot2 how to map variables to aesthetics, what graphical primitives to use, and it takes care of the details.

– Paraphrased from ggplot2’s website

Like the R-package dplyr for data manipulation, ggplot2 belongs to the so-called tidyverse, a cosmos of R-packages that have a common approach and a similar «feel». In this course, we prefer to use ggplot2 over R’s base graphic functions.

As usually with add-on R-packages you need to install ggplot2 once for your R-software on your computer.

install.packages("ggplot2")

Upon starting a new R-session you load the package so that all functions of ggplot2 are directly accessible.

library("ggplot2")

Otherwise, you will need to qualify each call to a ggplot2-function with ggplot2::, e.g., you would need to write ggplot2::aes() instead of simply aes().

Here in our primer, we start with a general explanation. Please read on even if it is not immediately clear what it means. The examples at the end hopefully help clarify the concepts. Finally, please play with the code yourself on your computer!

2.1 Big picture

Function calls in ggplot can become quite verbose but there is a general pattern that the ggplot2-authors succinctly describe as

«In most cases, you start with ggplot() and supply a dataset and aesthetic mapping (with aes() to parameter mapping=). You then add on

  • layers (like geom_point() or geom_histogram()),
  • scales (like scale_colour_brewer()),
  • faceting specifications (like facet_wrap()) and
  • coordinate systems (like coord_flip()).»

– cited from https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/#usage

The two most important steps in this scheme are:

  1. the aesthetic mapping that links data columns to plot properties
  2. the geometric layers that specify what type of plot you want

2.1.1 Mapping

The aesthetic mapping specifies which data columns correspond to what property in the plot. The mapping is constructed via a call to aes and given as parameter mapping= of the function call ggplot. For instance, for a scatterplot you need to specify which columns in the dataframe are mapped to the x- and y-axis. In the context of diamond data, one example would be mapping=aes(x = carat, y = price). Besides x= and y= for 2D-coordinates, other important aesthetics in a plot that can be mapped to data columns are

  • colour= that governs the colour of points, lines or areas.
  • shape= that governs the shape of points
  • size= that dictates the size of points
  • group= that indicates which observations belong together and form a sub-group

2.1.2 Layers

A layer describes how observations are rendered in the plot. In ggplot2, layers are created with function calls that start with geom_ For instance, a call to geom_point() yields a layer that will visualize observations as points in a 2D-space with x- and y-coordinates. geom_histogram() will create bins for a metric variable and count occurrences in the data and draw bars. Every aesthetic property of a plot that is not data-dependent but should get a specific value can be set within the geom_ function, for instance, geom_point(colour = "red") will draw red points at the coordinates specified in the dataframe.

A single plot can consist of multiple layers. Each layer is «added» to the ggplot object and it is natural to do this in a pipeline. The pipeline operator in ggplot2 is the plus sign +. So, with +, you literally «add» layer atop layer in a ggplot object.

It is easy to get confused with R’s native pipeline operator |> (since R version 4.1) or with dplyr’s pipeline operator %>% but eventually you might get used to the friendly coexistence of |> and +, eventually.

2.2 Examples

These explanations must be obscure at first read, but hang on, the examples below will hopefully help you out!

2.2.1 Histogram

Histograms are well-known to visualize the distribution of a single metric variable. To this end, the histogram coarsens the metric data into adjacent categories and visualizes the frequency (count) how often these categories occur in the sample.

Histogram of weight (column carat), using all available data:

ggplot(data = diamonds, mapping = aes(x = carat)) +
  geom_histogram()

This is a fundamental example that is comprised of the typical elements of a ggplot2-call. Notably, we have

  • supplied the data for the plot with argument data=diamonds
  • specified which to use data from column carat on the x-axis with argument mapping = aes(x = carat)
  • requested a histogram by adding the geometric layer + geom_histogram()

Now, we build on this basic example and showcase more possibilities of ggplot2:

Compare price distribution between cut-classes, using all data:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = price, colour = cut)) +
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = 500)

Frequency polygons (geom_freqpoly layer in ggplot) are like histograms but they facilitate to compare the distribution of the response across levels of a categorical variable. The grouping per cut-quality of the diamond is activated by the mapping of column cut to the graph property colour.

2.2.2 Scatter plot

We plot price (y-axis) versus weight (x-axis) in ggplot, exactly like we did in the initial base plot example.

Plot price (y-axis) versus weight (x-axis):

ggplot(diam, mapping = aes(x=carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point()

Plot price (y-axis) versus weight (x-axis), log-transformed x- & y-axis, fix point colour, add a trend line:

ggplot(diam, mapping = aes(x=carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point(col = "darkblue") + 
  geom_smooth(linetype = "dashed", size = 0.5, alpha = .4, se = FALSE) + 
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10()

Plot price (y-axis) versus weight (x-axis), colour according to cut, log-transformed x- & y-axis:

ggplot(diam, mapping = aes(x=carat, y = price, col = cut)) +
  geom_point() + 
  scale_x_log10() +
  scale_y_log10()

2.2.3 Boxplots & friends

Boxplots summarize a metric measurement variable and visually represent location and spread of the data using quantiles like the 25%-quantile, the 50%-quantile (median) and the 75%-quantile.

Plot price distribution per cut-group, log-transformed y-axis:

ggplot(diam, aes(x = cut, y = price)) +
  geom_boxplot() + 
  scale_y_log10()

Plot price distribution as violin plot per cut-group for all diamonds in diam with weight less than 1.75 carat on log-scale. Separate plots as per diamond colour:

# dplyr pipeline followed by ggplot pipeline
diam |> 
  dplyr::filter(carat < 1.75) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = cut, y = price)) +
    geom_violin() + 
    scale_y_log10() +
    facet_wrap(facets = vars(color))

The facet_wrap and facet_grid functions allow to have sub-panels in one big plot. These are informative when a relationship between two variables changes depending on a third variable.

2.2.4 Function graph

Sometimes, you quickly want to plot a graph of a function, e.g. you want to visualize \(y = \sqrt x · x - 1\). As you have seen, in ggplot2 you normally start with data that resides in a dataframe but for a function graph the relation between x and y is described by the function equation and you do not need any data. For this special requirement there is geom_function. A dataframe is not required, it is enough to specify the requested range on the x-axis.

The following plots shows the initially given function in the range from 0 to 5. For reference, we add the bisecting line

 ggplot() + xlim(c(0, 5)) + 
  geom_function(fun = \(x) sqrt(x) * x - 1) + 
  geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1, colour = "grey", linetype = "dashed")
